In article <7200.Sep2819.26.5693@silverton.berkeley.edu>,
D. J. Bernstein <djb@silverton.berkeley.edu> wrote:

>
>The phrase ``international arms dealer'' has no legal significance.
>DTC does not have two separate registration lists, one labelled
>``manufacturers of defense articles'' and the other labelled
>``international arms dealers.'' There is just one registration list.
>Manufacturers _and_ dealers must register, in exactly the same way, for
>exactly the same fees. A manufacturer who suddenly decides to export
>does not need to reregister.

Nevertheless, it is false to state (as some here did) that State said they
had to register as an International Arms Dealer. What State said was if they
made it they had to register as a maker. I can read the English Language in
the State Department letter. It's my mother tongue.

David
